Address - FeatureDataset

NameAddress
DescriptionThis dataset contains point address features such as the site address and other feature classes required for the administration of address information.

AddressEntrancePoint - FeatureClass

NameAddressEntrancePoint
ShapeTypePoint
FeatureTypeSimple
AliasNameAddress Entrance Points
HasMfalse
HasZfalse
HasAttachmentsfalse
DescriptionAddress entrance points represent the location where the public, or a service provider, would gain access to the specific site or service delivery address. In downtowns or other urban settings, many times the most direct access to an address may not be coincident with the location in which the address was assigned. In rural areas, the address entrance point could represent an entrance to a long or shared driveway.
TagsAddresses and Names

FieldDataTypeLengthAliasNameDescriptionDomainDefaultValueIsNullablePrecisionScale

CAPTUREMETHString30Capture MethodCapture method for address pointPointCollectionMethodtrue

ElectionResults - FeatureDataset

NameElectionResults
DescriptionThis dataset contains a collection of features used to report election results. The features are typically populated with results from an external election management system on a regular schedule during election night. The specific name of each feature class should reflect the political contests in your community and you may choose to use many of the feature classes provided as a model for other contests you wish to report on election night. Finally, the number of candidates present in each feature class will vary from election to election.

Encumbrance - FeatureClass

NameEncumbrance
ShapeTypePolygon
FeatureTypeSimple
AliasNameEncumbrances
HasMfalse
HasZfalse
HasAttachmentsfalse
DescriptionEncumbrances are limitations on the rights and use of the land. Easements are a common encumbrance but there are many others such as grazing rights, fishing rights, development rights, and floodplains. Legally an encumbrance is a right or interest in the land of another that may diminish its value but does not prevent its sale. Most encumbrances run with the land (consistent with the passing of the fee by conveyance). That is, they are tied to the land and will persist from owner to owner. Others exist at the pleasure of the owner, such as leases. Typically leases and similar encumbrances have an effective date and expiration date.
TagsEasement

FieldDataTypeLengthAliasNameDescriptionDomainDefaultValueIsNullablePrecisionScale
ENCUMIDString30Encumbrance Identification NumberThe identification number used to uniquely identify encumbrancestrue
SRCREFString100Document Index NumberThe index number assigned to the encumbrance or other reference documenttrue
ENCUMTYPEString30Encumbrance TypeThe type of encumbrancetrue
AREADouble8AreaThe area of the county in square milestrue
LASTUPDATEDate8Last Update DateThe date the feature was last updated in the maintenance databasetrue
LASTEDITORString50Last EditorThe user who performed the last updatetrue

NameCurrentSnowPlowLocation
ShapeTypePoint
FeatureTypeSimple
AliasNameCurrent Snow Plow Locations
HasMfalse
HasZtrue
HasAttachmentsfalse
DescriptionThe current location logged from telemetry devices deployed on, or with, snow plow equipment. The source of these locations is a Tracking Server feed configured for the telemetry provider and the frequency in which locations are added to this feature class is determined by the number of vehicles being logged and the frequency of the transmissions. In addition, the structure of this table is defined by the telemetry provider and information logged and shared for each vehicle.
